WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.375 --> 00:00:03.707
(gentle music)

2
00:00:03.707 --> 00:00:06.790
(transition dinging)

3
00:00:08.010 --> 00:00:09.780
<v Host>Dr. Holt is here.</v>

4
00:00:09.780 --> 00:00:12.450
She is gonna be leading our discussion this morning

5
00:00:12.450 --> 00:00:15.000
on some ENT issues.

6
00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:16.541
<v ->We are gonna be talking about ENT,</v>

7
00:00:16.541 --> 00:00:19.200
and I always said I wish I had something to disclose.

8
00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:21.480
I feel like that makes me sound a little cooler.

9
00:00:21.480 --> 00:00:23.070
Today, we're gonna spend most of our time

10
00:00:23.070 --> 00:00:26.190
talking about otitis media, sinusitis,

11
00:00:26.190 --> 00:00:27.510
and a little bit on vertigo.

12
00:00:27.510 --> 00:00:28.890
And then we're gonna just kind of do

13
00:00:28.890 --> 00:00:30.630
rapid fire board review,

14
00:00:30.630 --> 00:00:33.060
kind of one slide per topic on everything,

15
00:00:33.060 --> 00:00:38.060
from tinnitus to, I'd say some trauma for the ENT system,

16
00:00:38.340 --> 00:00:41.820
to Bell's Palsy, just real quick hitters for you guys.

17
00:00:41.820 --> 00:00:44.120
We're gonna get right into our first question.

18
00:00:45.060 --> 00:00:47.580
12-month-old male patient is brought into your office

19
00:00:47.580 --> 00:00:50.940
by his mother for fever, cough, and pooling on his left ear.

20
00:00:50.940 --> 00:00:54.240
He's afebrile in the office, playful, and interactive.

21
00:00:54.240 --> 00:00:55.380
When you examine his ear,

22
00:00:55.380 --> 00:00:58.410
the tympanic membranes are slightly erythematous,

23
00:00:58.410 --> 00:01:01.320
but he's uncooperative for pneumatic otoscopy.

24
00:01:01.320 --> 00:01:03.360
What is your diagnosis?

25
00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:06.270
URI with acute otitis media uncertain,

26
00:01:06.270 --> 00:01:08.490
otitis media with the effusion,

27
00:01:08.490 --> 00:01:11.883
acute otitis media, or Ramsay Hunt syndrome?

28
00:01:17.010 --> 00:01:20.850
Okay, URI With otitis media uncertain is the answer.

29
00:01:20.850 --> 00:01:23.370
For those that were toying with that acute otitis media,

30
00:01:23.370 --> 00:01:24.203
we're gonna talk through

31
00:01:24.203 --> 00:01:26.970
why we wouldn't call that in this kiddo.

32
00:01:26.970 --> 00:01:29.790
So everyone thinks their lecture is the most important.

33
00:01:29.790 --> 00:01:31.170
You know, I'm no different.

34
00:01:31.170 --> 00:01:34.500
When you look at the original 15 Choosing Wisely campaign

35
00:01:34.500 --> 00:01:36.390
from the American Academy of Family Physicians,

36
00:01:36.390 --> 00:01:38.700
two were from this lecture, 2 out of 15.

37
00:01:38.700 --> 00:01:41.190
So I'm gonna point those out when we get to them.

38
00:01:41.190 --> 00:01:42.750
Hint, this is one of them.

39
00:01:42.750 --> 00:01:45.210
So for diagnosing acute otitis media,

40
00:01:45.210 --> 00:01:47.640
we really wanna use stringent criteria.

41
00:01:47.640 --> 00:01:49.500
This is the most common disease

42
00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:51.600
diagnosed in children in our country.

43
00:01:51.600 --> 00:01:53.490
We give more than 20 million

44
00:01:53.490 --> 00:01:55.020
antibiotic prescriptions for this.

45
00:01:55.020 --> 00:01:56.790
So we don't wanna be over diagnosing

46
00:01:56.790 --> 00:01:59.550
and leading to more antibiotic resistance.

47
00:01:59.550 --> 00:02:00.630
We need three things.

48
00:02:00.630 --> 00:02:02.850
We need a sudden onset of symptoms,

49
00:02:02.850 --> 00:02:04.890
you have to prove that there's an effusion,

50
00:02:04.890 --> 00:02:07.110
that's the one we kind of fall apart on the most,

51
00:02:07.110 --> 00:02:09.930
and you have to see some acute signs of inflammation.

52
00:02:09.930 --> 00:02:12.390
So let's hit these one by one.

53
00:02:12.390 --> 00:02:13.290
What are these symptoms?

54
00:02:13.290 --> 00:02:15.180
This is should be a pretty sudden onset,

55
00:02:15.180 --> 00:02:17.940
a peak amount of symptoms within 48 hours.

56
00:02:17.940 --> 00:02:20.880
This is not, "My kid's been complaining for three weeks

57
00:02:20.880 --> 00:02:21.713
on ear pain."

58
00:02:21.713 --> 00:02:23.310
That doesn't fit.

59
00:02:23.310 --> 00:02:26.100
Severe symptoms are though a bit subjective.

60
00:02:26.100 --> 00:02:28.080
There are some objectivity put into here,

61
00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:31.800
fever greater than 39, which is equal to 102.2.

62
00:02:31.800 --> 00:02:32.910
That's a really weird temp.

63
00:02:32.910 --> 00:02:37.910
But above 102.2, that's a severe otitis media symptom.

64
00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:40.230
For that child that's non-verbal,

65
00:02:40.230 --> 00:02:41.430
you have to look at other things.

66
00:02:41.430 --> 00:02:42.960
Are they fussy? Are they not eating?

67
00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:43.950
Are they pulling at the ear?

68
00:02:43.950 --> 00:02:44.900
That kind of thing.

69
00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:48.510
The effusion, as I said, was the hardest part for us to do

70
00:02:48.510 --> 00:02:51.510
because you have to show that that TM isn't moving.

71
00:02:51.510 --> 00:02:53.190
You can't do this just visually.

72
00:02:53.190 --> 00:02:55.260
Just by like seeing fluid behind the ear,

73
00:02:55.260 --> 00:02:56.580
that doesn't count.

74
00:02:56.580 --> 00:02:58.350
So you really have to demonstrate

75
00:02:58.350 --> 00:03:00.180
that there's a middle ear effusion.

76
00:03:00.180 --> 00:03:02.340
The best way to do that is that little bulb thing

77
00:03:02.340 --> 00:03:04.110
that goes on our otoscopes, right?

78
00:03:04.110 --> 00:03:06.750
If they're not moving with that, that's an indication.

79
00:03:06.750 --> 00:03:10.140
So pneumatic otoscopy is the standard of care.

80
00:03:10.140 --> 00:03:11.790
It is better than any of the other tests.

81
00:03:11.790 --> 00:03:13.440
It's better than the old Weber.

82
00:03:13.440 --> 00:03:14.970
I'm sure you use that Weber test

83
00:03:14.970 --> 00:03:16.920
with your tuning fork all the time.

84
00:03:16.920 --> 00:03:19.470
It is certainly better too than tympanometry,

85
00:03:19.470 --> 00:03:21.060
which is maybe surprises some people.

86
00:03:21.060 --> 00:03:24.690
We will talk about later when tympanometry is needed.

87
00:03:24.690 --> 00:03:26.160
Inflammation, I think, we're pretty good

88
00:03:26.160 --> 00:03:27.120
at looking at this, right?

89
00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:28.789
It looks bulging, full.

90
00:03:28.789 --> 00:03:31.350
There's sometimes bullae on it.

91
00:03:31.350 --> 00:03:33.900
Sometimes there's acute drainage coming out of it,

92
00:03:33.900 --> 00:03:35.400
but you have to pay attention for that

93
00:03:35.400 --> 00:03:37.380
to not be otitis externa, okay?

94
00:03:37.380 --> 00:03:39.390
So that can be tricky sometimes.

95
00:03:39.390 --> 00:03:41.430
Erythema alone, not very helpful.

96
00:03:41.430 --> 00:03:43.470
We just learned about positive predictive value

97
00:03:43.470 --> 00:03:45.180
in the last lecture,

98
00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:48.060
only 15% positive predictive value

99
00:03:48.060 --> 00:03:50.760
when it comes to erythema alone.

100
00:03:50.760 --> 00:03:53.220
So that's why our kiddo in that description

101
00:03:53.220 --> 00:03:54.990
didn't have acute otitis media.

102
00:03:54.990 --> 00:03:57.750
We hadn't proven that he had effusion.

103
00:03:57.750 --> 00:04:00.810
So how can you tell if it's acute otitis media

104
00:04:00.810 --> 00:04:05.310
versus just effusion, otitis media with effusion?

105
00:04:05.310 --> 00:04:06.990
Those can be tricky.

106
00:04:06.990 --> 00:04:09.660
They both have effusion by definition, right?

107
00:04:09.660 --> 00:04:11.430
But there's a lot of absence

108
00:04:11.430 --> 00:04:13.230
of these acute inflammation symptoms.

109
00:04:13.230 --> 00:04:14.767
This could be more the kid is like,

110
00:04:14.767 --> 00:04:17.220
"Ah, the ears just been achy for a long time."

111
00:04:17.220 --> 00:04:18.960
That could be more the effusion.

112
00:04:18.960 --> 00:04:20.610
You're not usually gonna see a fever here.

113
00:04:20.610 --> 00:04:21.630
So if you're seeing fever,

114
00:04:21.630 --> 00:04:23.730
that should point you along the other line.

115
00:04:23.730 --> 00:04:26.010
But visually, this is kind of the difference, right?

116
00:04:26.010 --> 00:04:28.290
That picture on the left, acute otitis media,

117
00:04:28.290 --> 00:04:29.310
it looks like it's gonna blow.

118
00:04:29.310 --> 00:04:30.660
It's pretty exciting.

119
00:04:30.660 --> 00:04:32.928
I think the otitis media with effusion kind of looks cute.

120
00:04:32.928 --> 00:04:36.510
It's like round bubbles, it's kind of artistic.

121
00:04:36.510 --> 00:04:39.870
Those look different and those feel different to the kid.

122
00:04:39.870 --> 00:04:41.700
When do we need this tympanometry?

123
00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:45.990
When you can't tell with pneumatic otoscopy.

124
00:04:45.990 --> 00:04:47.617
If you do the little bulb thing and you're like,

125
00:04:47.617 --> 00:04:48.750
"I don't know,"

126
00:04:48.750 --> 00:04:50.790
then you could think about using this tympanometry.

127
00:04:50.790 --> 00:04:53.160
but it's not for kids under seven months of age.

128
00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:54.600
Their canals are so pliable,

129
00:04:54.600 --> 00:04:57.270
you can make them be whatever you want them to be.

130
00:04:57.270 --> 00:05:00.180
We have occasionally seen this on ITEs and the boards.

131
00:05:00.180 --> 00:05:01.500
And if they show you a curve,

132
00:05:01.500 --> 00:05:03.270
they're usually gonna show you this B curve,

133
00:05:03.270 --> 00:05:04.770
which is a flat line.

134
00:05:04.770 --> 00:05:06.720
So when you're kind of panicking in the moment of the test,

135
00:05:06.720 --> 00:05:08.160
you're thinking, "What are they putting this on there?

136
00:05:08.160 --> 00:05:10.110
There's nothing on this curve. It's empty."

137
00:05:10.110 --> 00:05:11.100
It's that flat line.

138
00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:13.560
They want you to see that membrane is not moving.

139
00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:16.140
So that shows that there's an effusion.

140
00:05:16.140 --> 00:05:18.090
The type C curves are less helpful.

141
00:05:18.090 --> 00:05:19.920
So I don't think they'll put those on there,

142
00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:21.360
and that A curve is normal.

143
00:05:21.360 --> 00:05:22.470
So they could put that on there

144
00:05:22.470 --> 00:05:25.263
to show you that this is not an acute otitis media.

145
00:05:27.180 --> 00:05:28.800
Okay, let's get into our next question here.

146
00:05:28.800 --> 00:05:30.990
That 22-month-old male patient is brought to you

147
00:05:30.990 --> 00:05:34.710
for crying in an obvious acute distress from right ear pain.

148
00:05:34.710 --> 00:05:36.146
Fever of 103.6.

149
00:05:36.146 --> 00:05:40.080
On exam, it is immobile, bulging, erythematous.

150
00:05:40.080 --> 00:05:42.120
What is the best treatment option?

151
00:05:42.120 --> 00:05:43.290
Do not use antibiotics

152
00:05:43.290 --> 00:05:45.900
because this is probably a viral illness.

153
00:05:45.900 --> 00:05:47.790
Have the parents observe for 48 hours

154
00:05:47.790 --> 00:05:50.340
and treat with antibiotics if no improvement.

155
00:05:50.340 --> 00:05:53.250
Treat with antihistamines and decongestants alone.

156
00:05:53.250 --> 00:05:55.143
Start antibiotics immediately.

157
00:06:00.330 --> 00:06:01.163
Okay, what do we think?

158
00:06:01.163 --> 00:06:03.309
75%, start antibiotics immediately.

159
00:06:03.309 --> 00:06:04.590
Excellent job.

160
00:06:04.590 --> 00:06:06.720
So we're gonna find out why observation

161
00:06:06.720 --> 00:06:08.340
may not be appropriate in this kid

162
00:06:08.340 --> 00:06:11.340
because for other kids, it might be appropriate.

163
00:06:11.340 --> 00:06:12.810
So what is helpful for all kids?

164
00:06:12.810 --> 00:06:13.740
Pain management.

165
00:06:13.740 --> 00:06:15.750
Ibuprofen, acetaminophen, that's important,

166
00:06:15.750 --> 00:06:18.180
whether you're choosing to do antibiotics or not.

167
00:06:18.180 --> 00:06:19.860
All those other things, not helpful.

168
00:06:19.860 --> 00:06:22.620
Decongestants, antihistamines, no improvement.

169
00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:24.960
There are randomized controlled trials looking at this

170
00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:26.400
and they did not help.

171
00:06:26.400 --> 00:06:28.890
The only thing is antihistamines maybe provide

172
00:06:28.890 --> 00:06:30.660
some benefit in older kids

173
00:06:30.660 --> 00:06:33.900
who have a lot of congestion along with otitis media,

174
00:06:33.900 --> 00:06:35.973
but for the general person, not helpful.

175
00:06:36.960 --> 00:06:37.920
This is kind of nice.

176
00:06:37.920 --> 00:06:39.900
So much of medicine changes all the time.

177
00:06:39.900 --> 00:06:42.240
This hasn't changed since we were all in med school.

178
00:06:42.240 --> 00:06:44.685
Strep pneumo, H. Flu, Moraxella catarrhalis.

179
00:06:44.685 --> 00:06:46.770
Moraxella has changed names a few times,

180
00:06:46.770 --> 00:06:48.690
but it's still the same bug.

181
00:06:48.690 --> 00:06:50.640
When do we start thinking about observation?

182
00:06:50.640 --> 00:06:52.020
This really came out of Europe,

183
00:06:52.020 --> 00:06:54.330
and this is good reason to think about this.

184
00:06:54.330 --> 00:06:59.330
61% of symptoms resolved within one day, 80% by three days.

185
00:06:59.430 --> 00:07:01.800
So maybe all these kids don't really need antibiotics.

186
00:07:01.800 --> 00:07:04.140
So how do we know?

187
00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:05.610
This is an important slide.

188
00:07:05.610 --> 00:07:07.800
So if you're under six months of age

189
00:07:07.800 --> 00:07:09.750
and you diagnose acute titis media

190
00:07:09.750 --> 00:07:11.160
with those three components,

191
00:07:11.160 --> 00:07:13.083
they get antibiotics, regardless.

192
00:07:13.950 --> 00:07:16.590
If you're 6 to 23 months of age,

193
00:07:16.590 --> 00:07:18.780
there's two criteria where you would need antibiotics.

194
00:07:18.780 --> 00:07:21.900
It has to be bilateral or severe.

195
00:07:21.900 --> 00:07:24.390
So if it's unilateral and not severe symptoms,

196
00:07:24.390 --> 00:07:26.940
you could hold on antibiotics.

197
00:07:26.940 --> 00:07:30.240
If you're over two, or 24 months,

198
00:07:30.240 --> 00:07:31.950
you have to have severe disease

199
00:07:31.950 --> 00:07:33.420
to be treated with antibiotics.

200
00:07:33.420 --> 00:07:34.470
Otherwise, it's recommended

201
00:07:34.470 --> 00:07:36.370
that you have a period of observation.

202
00:07:37.890 --> 00:07:39.545
What does that observation look like?

203
00:07:39.545 --> 00:07:41.520
You have to be able to see the kid back,

204
00:07:41.520 --> 00:07:42.720
if they're not doing well.

205
00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:45.330
And really, it usually involves a reexamination

206
00:07:45.330 --> 00:07:47.610
to make sure you haven't missed the diagnosis.

207
00:07:47.610 --> 00:07:49.470
Some people will opt for that last option,

208
00:07:49.470 --> 00:07:51.480
which is postdating scripts.

209
00:07:51.480 --> 00:07:52.770
I'm gonna give you this antibiotic,

210
00:07:52.770 --> 00:07:54.060
but you're not gonna start it yet

211
00:07:54.060 --> 00:07:55.560
'cause I'm not even gonna start a fill date

212
00:07:55.560 --> 00:07:57.120
until three days from now.

213
00:07:57.120 --> 00:07:58.020
So if they're that kid

214
00:07:58.020 --> 00:07:59.910
with 80% getting better in three days,

215
00:07:59.910 --> 00:08:01.890
hopefully, the parents won't fill it.

216
00:08:01.890 --> 00:08:03.510
What does AFP say?

217
00:08:03.510 --> 00:08:04.920
Strength the recommendation B,

218
00:08:04.920 --> 00:08:08.433
observation for 48 to 72 hours for those low risk kids.

219
00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:11.460
This is one of our Choose Wisely campaigns.

220
00:08:11.460 --> 00:08:13.853
So you already have one under your belt right here.

221
00:08:15.390 --> 00:08:17.520
All right, here comes a little bit of math.

222
00:08:17.520 --> 00:08:20.190
You diagnose acute otitis media with severe symptoms

223
00:08:20.190 --> 00:08:23.370
in a 22-month-old patient who weighs 20 kilos,

224
00:08:23.370 --> 00:08:25.560
what is the most appropriate treatment?

225
00:08:25.560 --> 00:08:29.790
amoxicillin 900, amoxicillin 1,800 for the day,

226
00:08:29.790 --> 00:08:31.920
amoxicillin-clavulanate 900,

227
00:08:31.920 --> 00:08:34.883
or amoxicillin-clavulanate 1,800?

228
00:08:40.080 --> 00:08:41.250
Look at you, guys. Good.

229
00:08:41.250 --> 00:08:43.770
60 something percent of you got amoxicillin

230
00:08:43.770 --> 00:08:44.760
is the treatment of choice,

231
00:08:44.760 --> 00:08:47.670
and it is the higher dose amoxicillin.

232
00:08:47.670 --> 00:08:50.940
So AAP and AFP have solid agreement on this.

233
00:08:50.940 --> 00:08:54.030
amoxicillin, roughly 90 mgs per kg per day,

234
00:08:54.030 --> 00:08:56.341
and you divide that every 12 hours.

235
00:08:56.341 --> 00:08:58.560
Who needs that Augmentin option?

236
00:08:58.560 --> 00:09:01.350
If you have been on other antibiotics in the last 30 days,

237
00:09:01.350 --> 00:09:02.760
you could bump to that.

238
00:09:02.760 --> 00:09:05.070
If you have what looks like H. Flu,

239
00:09:05.070 --> 00:09:07.080
your eyes are very leaky.

240
00:09:07.080 --> 00:09:10.080
That's an indication that Augmentin might be better for you.

241
00:09:10.080 --> 00:09:13.320
And if you're taking antibiotics for recurrent otitis media,

242
00:09:13.320 --> 00:09:14.640
and I hope you're not because

243
00:09:14.640 --> 00:09:16.590
that guideline changed in 2013,

244
00:09:16.590 --> 00:09:19.320
but if you happen to be taking daily prophylaxis,

245
00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:20.640
that would be a kid who would benefit

246
00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:22.740
from Augmentin instead.

247
00:09:22.740 --> 00:09:25.740
Oh, the penicillin allergy. Always a fun one, right?

248
00:09:25.740 --> 00:09:27.450
We do know that 90% of people

249
00:09:27.450 --> 00:09:29.370
who have penicillin allergy on their chart

250
00:09:29.370 --> 00:09:31.050
do not have penicillin allergy.

251
00:09:31.050 --> 00:09:32.760
And so you use that in your mind.

252
00:09:32.760 --> 00:09:36.030
If this was a non anaphylactic type of reaction in the past,

253
00:09:36.030 --> 00:09:39.210
you can feel very comfortable doing cephalosporin.

254
00:09:39.210 --> 00:09:41.430
If it was anaphylaxis in the past,

255
00:09:41.430 --> 00:09:42.960
there is some cross reactivity.

256
00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:47.040
So in this case, azithromycin becomes our top choice.

257
00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:48.713
Those others are not recommended.

258
00:09:48.713 --> 00:09:51.360
Trimethoprim-sulfa, because of resistance,

259
00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:53.010
and Levaquin as well with resistance.

260
00:09:53.010 --> 00:09:55.560
But we don't do a lot of quinolones anyway in kids.

261
00:09:56.610 --> 00:09:57.660
Duration of treatment.

262
00:09:57.660 --> 00:09:59.520
This has been studied for quite a while now.

263
00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:00.780
We have a solid answer.

264
00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:02.520
10 days. 10 days,

265
00:10:02.520 --> 00:10:05.220
Shorter courses do not have better outcomes.

266
00:10:05.220 --> 00:10:07.890
So five to seven days do not work better.

267
00:10:07.890 --> 00:10:09.300
And there was actually no difference

268
00:10:09.300 --> 00:10:10.620
in drug resistance in the group.

269
00:10:10.620 --> 00:10:13.290
So 10 days is your solid answer there.

270
00:10:13.290 --> 00:10:15.300
So you treat that kid with acute otitis media

271
00:10:15.300 --> 00:10:17.730
with antibiotics, see him back four weeks later.

272
00:10:17.730 --> 00:10:21.150
He's asymptomatic, but he still has a middle ear effusion.

273
00:10:21.150 --> 00:10:22.440
What's your recommendation?

274
00:10:22.440 --> 00:10:24.990
Reassurance and reevaluate in two months,

275
00:10:24.990 --> 00:10:27.930
oral and antihistamines for 30 days,

276
00:10:27.930 --> 00:10:31.080
re-treat, but this time bump up to that Augmentin,

277
00:10:31.080 --> 00:10:33.210
do nasal steroids for 30 days,

278
00:10:33.210 --> 00:10:36.063
or do an ENT referral to consider tubes?

279
00:10:40.830 --> 00:10:43.560
Wonderful! Reassurance and reevaluate.

280
00:10:43.560 --> 00:10:45.420
You wisely knew that this is normal.

281
00:10:45.420 --> 00:10:47.730
That effusion can last a long time.

282
00:10:47.730 --> 00:10:49.440
70% at that two week mark,

283
00:10:49.440 --> 00:10:51.257
it continues to go down to about 10%

284
00:10:51.257 --> 00:10:53.310
at that three-month mark.

285
00:10:53.310 --> 00:10:54.780
So that's usually when we recommend

286
00:10:54.780 --> 00:10:56.670
following up is like a 8 to 12 weeks,

287
00:10:56.670 --> 00:10:58.530
just to kind of see if it's gone.

288
00:10:58.530 --> 00:11:01.290
If it is a kid who's at that language acquisition phase,

289
00:11:01.290 --> 00:11:03.150
you wanna make sure we're not inhibiting

290
00:11:03.150 --> 00:11:04.533
their ability to do that.

291
00:11:05.550 --> 00:11:06.450
Now this is different.

292
00:11:06.450 --> 00:11:08.400
This is a kid who is still symptomatic,

293
00:11:08.400 --> 00:11:10.170
a persistent acute otitis media.

294
00:11:10.170 --> 00:11:13.680
They're just not getting better after 48 to 72 hours.

295
00:11:13.680 --> 00:11:15.690
This is important to see them back in the office.

296
00:11:15.690 --> 00:11:17.730
If you thought they had acute otitis media

297
00:11:17.730 --> 00:11:19.710
and you gave them antibiotics that were appropriate

298
00:11:19.710 --> 00:11:21.780
and they're still not better, see them back.

299
00:11:21.780 --> 00:11:23.610
Make sure you're not missing a mastoiditis

300
00:11:23.610 --> 00:11:25.080
or something else.

301
00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:27.690
If you say, "Yeah, that's still acute otitis media,"

302
00:11:27.690 --> 00:11:30.030
then you wanna switch to one of these second line agents.

303
00:11:30.030 --> 00:11:32.160
So Augmentin is gonna be your first choice,

304
00:11:32.160 --> 00:11:33.760
other, cephalosporin, and so on.

305
00:11:34.710 --> 00:11:37.689
We talked about recurrent acute otitis media very briefly

306
00:11:37.689 --> 00:11:40.110
and that antibiotics are not recommended.

307
00:11:40.110 --> 00:11:41.610
They have said that in 2013

308
00:11:41.610 --> 00:11:45.000
and reconfirm that multiple times since.

309
00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:47.190
Give them all the vaccines. That does help, right?

310
00:11:47.190 --> 00:11:49.620
Flu and pneumococcal in particular make a difference

311
00:11:49.620 --> 00:11:52.950
in decreasing the incidence of acute otitis media.

312
00:11:52.950 --> 00:11:54.900
Don't smoke, wonderful advice.

313
00:11:54.900 --> 00:11:57.800
If that's a choice on the boards, always pick that choice.

314
00:11:59.010 --> 00:12:01.080
Bottle feeding is a risk factor.

315
00:12:01.080 --> 00:12:02.850
Pacifier use is a risk factor,

316
00:12:02.850 --> 00:12:05.100
and that's because that sort of constant sucking

317
00:12:05.100 --> 00:12:07.140
keeps that eustachian tube open,

318
00:12:07.140 --> 00:12:10.320
which allows bacteria to get into the system.

319
00:12:10.320 --> 00:12:12.240
If you breastfeed for six or more months,

320
00:12:12.240 --> 00:12:13.470
that's very protective.

321
00:12:13.470 --> 00:12:15.630
So that's something we really wanna encourage.

322
00:12:15.630 --> 00:12:16.560
And then daycare,

323
00:12:16.560 --> 00:12:18.360
a lot of parents don't have a choice about that,

324
00:12:18.360 --> 00:12:20.250
but daycare attendance does increase the risk

325
00:12:20.250 --> 00:12:21.663
of acute otitis media.

326
00:12:22.710 --> 00:12:24.900
So we know that this effusion can be normal.

327
00:12:24.900 --> 00:12:26.280
When do we start getting worried

328
00:12:26.280 --> 00:12:27.630
if it still hasn't gone away?

329
00:12:27.630 --> 00:12:28.590
And so as we said,

330
00:12:28.590 --> 00:12:31.200
watchful waiting for three months is appropriate.

331
00:12:31.200 --> 00:12:32.880
If it's still going on at three months,

332
00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:34.500
you do wanna check in on that hearing

333
00:12:34.500 --> 00:12:36.480
because of language acquisition.

334
00:12:36.480 --> 00:12:38.421
At that point, we used to send everybody for tubes.

335
00:12:38.421 --> 00:12:40.668
Now it's pretty controversial.

336
00:12:40.668 --> 00:12:45.240
A patient-oriented evidence that matters from AFP in 2016

337
00:12:45.240 --> 00:12:47.460
looked at 16 randomized controlled trials,

338
00:12:47.460 --> 00:12:51.270
no hearing benefit 12 to 24 months after getting tubes.

339
00:12:51.270 --> 00:12:54.030
So, hm, now we're not sure what to do with it.

340
00:12:54.030 --> 00:12:56.877
There is still some data on recurrent acute otitis media

341
00:12:56.877 --> 00:12:59.730
getting tubes, but if it's just a persistent effusion,

342
00:12:59.730 --> 00:13:01.530
it's a little more of a waiting game.

343
00:13:01.530 --> 00:13:03.870
And unfortunately, all those treatments at the bottom

344
00:13:03.870 --> 00:13:05.820
have been tried and not helpful.

345
00:13:05.820 --> 00:13:08.070
So nasal steroids, oral steroids, you name it,

346
00:13:08.070 --> 00:13:10.650
none of those have made a difference in the effusion.

347
00:13:10.650 --> 00:13:13.893
So this is a conversation with your parents here.

348
00:13:13.893 --> 00:13:17.250
This is one of those rapid fire tinnitus here.

349
00:13:17.250 --> 00:13:18.210
You hear sound,

350
00:13:18.210 --> 00:13:20.610
but there's actually no acoustic stimulus for that sound.

351
00:13:20.610 --> 00:13:23.310
This is a symptom, not a diagnosis.

352
00:13:23.310 --> 00:13:25.020
Most commonly, it's idiopathic,

353
00:13:25.020 --> 00:13:26.460
which is very frustrating for you

354
00:13:26.460 --> 00:13:28.500
and very frustrating for your patients.

355
00:13:28.500 --> 00:13:31.620
The second most common cause is sensory neural hearing loss.

356
00:13:31.620 --> 00:13:33.240
You see some of the other causes up there.

357
00:13:33.240 --> 00:13:36.510
Some of those will point to it based on the history.

358
00:13:36.510 --> 00:13:39.000
Meds are a big thing. Look through the med list.

359
00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.220
That can be something you can do to turn this around.

360
00:13:41.220 --> 00:13:43.140
So if they're on chronic NSAIDs,

361
00:13:43.140 --> 00:13:45.720
if they're on chronic antimicrobials for prophylaxis,

362
00:13:45.720 --> 00:13:46.818
for example, loop diuretics,

363
00:13:46.818 --> 00:13:48.930
there's a bunch of things on this list,

364
00:13:48.930 --> 00:13:50.370
but those are the big ones.

365
00:13:50.370 --> 00:13:52.140
Potentially switching them off of those

366
00:13:52.140 --> 00:13:55.380
may really make your patient's life a lot better.

367
00:13:55.380 --> 00:13:57.180
What does expert opinion say?

368
00:13:57.180 --> 00:13:59.520
Don't do anything other than get a history and physical.

369
00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:01.950
If the history and physical points you somewhere else

370
00:14:01.950 --> 00:14:05.220
other than a idiopathic, then you can do some workup.

371
00:14:05.220 --> 00:14:07.200
And if you have a bunch of hearing loss,

372
00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:09.030
you might need an audiogram, right?

373
00:14:09.030 --> 00:14:10.710
If you're having a lot of vertigo,

374
00:14:10.710 --> 00:14:12.660
you might need a vestibular eval.

375
00:14:12.660 --> 00:14:16.860
If it's pulsatile, you might think about getting an MRA.

376
00:14:16.860 --> 00:14:19.410
If it's unilateral, you do have to consider

377
00:14:19.410 --> 00:14:21.600
is this one of those schwannomas, okay?

378
00:14:21.600 --> 00:14:24.270
So hearing loss should be a really big component of that.

379
00:14:24.270 --> 00:14:26.970
Vertigo should be a much smaller component.

380
00:14:26.970 --> 00:14:29.730
And then if you don't think they have any of those things

381
00:14:29.730 --> 00:14:30.780
and you can't reverse it

382
00:14:30.780 --> 00:14:32.370
and they're not on any of those meds,

383
00:14:32.370 --> 00:14:34.260
CBT actually has some decent data

384
00:14:34.260 --> 00:14:36.840
strength of recommendation B that that can help them

385
00:14:36.840 --> 00:14:38.820
for that sort of like, "Oh, I'm gonna go bonkers

386
00:14:38.820 --> 00:14:40.570
'cause my ears are always ringing."

387
00:14:41.730 --> 00:14:44.940
Sudden sensory neuro hearing loss,

388
00:14:44.940 --> 00:14:47.400
again, idiopathic up to 90% of the time.

389
00:14:47.400 --> 00:14:49.680
That's frustrating, but this is kind of a new thing.

390
00:14:49.680 --> 00:14:51.120
Hyperbaric oxygen therapy

391
00:14:51.120 --> 00:14:52.890
has pretty darn good data for this.

392
00:14:52.890 --> 00:14:55.230
So if you start some, if someone has a sudden onset

393
00:14:55.230 --> 00:14:57.750
and you get them into treatment relatively quickly,

394
00:14:57.750 --> 00:15:00.540
number needed to treat is only 5.3.

395
00:15:00.540 --> 00:15:02.910
That's pretty great NNT in medicine.

396
00:15:02.910 --> 00:15:06.450
Oral corticosteroids have pretty mixed data.

397
00:15:06.450 --> 00:15:07.380
Pretty equivocal,

398
00:15:07.380 --> 00:15:09.630
but they are still recommended in the guidelines

399
00:15:09.630 --> 00:15:11.780
because they help some people, essentially.

400
00:15:12.660 --> 00:15:15.120
The things that don't work, calcium channel blockers,

401
00:15:15.120 --> 00:15:17.700
anti-platelets, antibiotic course doesn't work

402
00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:19.830
unless you're diagnosing acute otitis media

403
00:15:19.830 --> 00:15:22.200
as the source of their hearing loss.

404
00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:25.110
If it persists, you can think about some other work up here,

405
00:15:25.110 --> 00:15:26.550
but most of the time,

406
00:15:26.550 --> 00:15:28.700
get that hyperbaric, if you can get 'em in.

407
00:15:29.850 --> 00:15:32.130
All right, moving to our next big category here.

408
00:15:32.130 --> 00:15:34.560
43-year-old male patient presents to your office

409
00:15:34.560 --> 00:15:37.470
with five days of nasal congestion and headache.

410
00:15:37.470 --> 00:15:40.710
Temperature is 100.8, purulent rhinorrhea,

411
00:15:40.710 --> 00:15:42.300
minimal tenderness to pop patient

412
00:15:42.300 --> 00:15:44.700
over the frontal maxillary sinuses.

413
00:15:44.700 --> 00:15:46.110
What's our next step?

414
00:15:46.110 --> 00:15:48.060
Transilluminate those sinuses,

415
00:15:48.060 --> 00:15:49.920
get a sinus X-ray,

416
00:15:49.920 --> 00:15:52.860
treat with nasal saline and topical steroids,

417
00:15:52.860 --> 00:15:54.933
or treat with amoxicillin-clavulanate?

418
00:16:00.570 --> 00:16:03.720
Treat with nasal saline topical steroids is the answer.

419
00:16:03.720 --> 00:16:04.553
Good work.

420
00:16:04.553 --> 00:16:06.570
About 68% of you got that.

421
00:16:06.570 --> 00:16:09.210
Some of you were tempted to treat with antibiotics.

422
00:16:09.210 --> 00:16:12.450
This is gonna be the next Choosing Wisely campaign.

423
00:16:12.450 --> 00:16:14.700
So what is this acute rhinosinusitis?

424
00:16:14.700 --> 00:16:16.500
Less than four weeks of symptoms

425
00:16:16.500 --> 00:16:18.180
is a really important differentiation.

426
00:16:18.180 --> 00:16:20.130
So get that on your history.

427
00:16:20.130 --> 00:16:24.150
Etiology, only about 2% is bacterial.

428
00:16:24.150 --> 00:16:27.720
Patients hate this answer, okay, but that is what it is.

429
00:16:27.720 --> 00:16:30.000
How do you know if it might be one of those people

430
00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:31.440
that is that bacterial?

431
00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:33.270
You dig into it from your history.

432
00:16:33.270 --> 00:16:36.090
Symptoms more than seven days is an important piece.

433
00:16:36.090 --> 00:16:37.350
Progression of symptoms.

434
00:16:37.350 --> 00:16:38.640
It's not a flat symptoms.

435
00:16:38.640 --> 00:16:41.520
They're continuing to escalate in their symptoms.

436
00:16:41.520 --> 00:16:45.330
Moderate to severe pain and fever over 101.

437
00:16:45.330 --> 00:16:47.850
Bimodal disease is another really good clue.

438
00:16:47.850 --> 00:16:49.920
I had it at first, I got better,

439
00:16:49.920 --> 00:16:51.690
and then it suddenly got worse again.

440
00:16:51.690 --> 00:16:53.760
That's usually the viral component at the beginning

441
00:16:53.760 --> 00:16:56.790
and a secondary bacterial component thereafter.

442
00:16:56.790 --> 00:16:59.010
Tobacco use, again, as a risk factor,

443
00:16:59.010 --> 00:17:01.170
as well as chronic allergies.

444
00:17:01.170 --> 00:17:02.760
All this stuff is not helpful.

445
00:17:02.760 --> 00:17:04.860
So you don't have to put the light up to their face

446
00:17:04.860 --> 00:17:06.750
even though that feels kind of fun and exciting.

447
00:17:06.750 --> 00:17:08.253
It does not help you.

448
00:17:08.253 --> 00:17:11.880
Not swabbing their nose for cultures, no help.

449
00:17:11.880 --> 00:17:14.070
If you end up having to send 'em to ENT later,

450
00:17:14.070 --> 00:17:16.260
there is some evidence for endoscopic cultures,

451
00:17:16.260 --> 00:17:18.330
but not the cultures we could do.

452
00:17:18.330 --> 00:17:19.830
And none of that imaging is needed,

453
00:17:19.830 --> 00:17:22.413
unless you think some other diagnosis is going on.

454
00:17:23.730 --> 00:17:27.120
So viral rhinosinusitis is a self-limited disease.

455
00:17:27.120 --> 00:17:29.280
There are a lot of these patients showing up in your office,

456
00:17:29.280 --> 00:17:31.290
in the ER and urgent cares.

457
00:17:31.290 --> 00:17:34.080
What has strength of recommendation A is supportive care.

458
00:17:34.080 --> 00:17:35.970
Analgesics, nasal saline sprays,

459
00:17:35.970 --> 00:17:38.158
and actually irrigations do better here.

460
00:17:38.158 --> 00:17:40.710
Intranasal corticosteroids.

461
00:17:40.710 --> 00:17:43.583
The next best category you could consider is ipratropium.

462
00:17:43.583 --> 00:17:45.690
There's some NIH data that says

463
00:17:45.690 --> 00:17:47.927
that's really helpful for rhinorrhea,

464
00:17:47.927 --> 00:17:50.370
but not much for pain of congestion.

465
00:17:50.370 --> 00:17:51.930
So if it's really they're going crazy

466
00:17:51.930 --> 00:17:53.550
'cause their nose is running all the time at work,

467
00:17:53.550 --> 00:17:55.290
that could be an option.

468
00:17:55.290 --> 00:17:58.200
Topical decongestants, the old ephedrine.

469
00:17:58.200 --> 00:17:59.520
It does actually work,

470
00:17:59.520 --> 00:18:01.879
but you really have to have a great patient

471
00:18:01.879 --> 00:18:03.390
who's willing to stop it at that third day,

472
00:18:03.390 --> 00:18:04.290
'cause otherwise,

473
00:18:04.290 --> 00:18:06.750
they're gonna just have rebound afterwards.

474
00:18:06.750 --> 00:18:08.820
All the things at the bottom are not recommended.

475
00:18:08.820 --> 00:18:11.700
I wanna specifically call out oral decongestion,

476
00:18:11.700 --> 00:18:14.010
pseudoephedrine, not recommended.

477
00:18:14.010 --> 00:18:16.950
Multiple randomized controlled trials with no benefit.

478
00:18:16.950 --> 00:18:19.830
If anyone saw the FDA came out in September of last year

479
00:18:19.830 --> 00:18:21.330
and said, "No more."

480
00:18:21.330 --> 00:18:25.230
And it's still a $2.8 billion industry, pseudoephedrine.

481
00:18:25.230 --> 00:18:27.720
So that's a great opportunity to educate your patients

482
00:18:27.720 --> 00:18:29.270
on why that's not a great idea.

483
00:18:31.680 --> 00:18:33.930
So what about this bacterial process?

484
00:18:33.930 --> 00:18:34.763
How do we know?

485
00:18:34.763 --> 00:18:36.817
Strength of recommendation A says,

486
00:18:36.817 --> 00:18:39.570
"Watchful waiting without antibiotics is important."

487
00:18:39.570 --> 00:18:41.910
Supportive treatment for that first seven days.

488
00:18:41.910 --> 00:18:44.460
Again, 70% are gonna resolve by that one week.

489
00:18:44.460 --> 00:18:45.990
So just support them through that,.

490
00:18:45.990 --> 00:18:48.180
the vast majority will get better.

491
00:18:48.180 --> 00:18:49.560
It's only expert opinion

492
00:18:49.560 --> 00:18:52.500
that says do antibiotics after the seven-day mark.

493
00:18:52.500 --> 00:18:54.150
Another nice study came out AFP,

494
00:18:54.150 --> 00:18:57.450
number needed to treat with antibiotics for benefit is 17.

495
00:18:57.450 --> 00:18:59.280
You're like, "Well, that feels pretty good."

496
00:18:59.280 --> 00:19:02.100
Number needed to harm with antibiotics is eight.

497
00:19:02.100 --> 00:19:04.950
So that's a number that I share with my patients as well.

498
00:19:06.270 --> 00:19:08.550
There's that Choosing Wisely number two,

499
00:19:08.550 --> 00:19:10.623
so don't do so much antibiotics.

500
00:19:11.700 --> 00:19:13.110
What does IDSA say?

501
00:19:13.110 --> 00:19:15.510
The International Disease Society of America,

502
00:19:15.510 --> 00:19:18.300
Infectious Disease Society of America, excuse me.

503
00:19:18.300 --> 00:19:20.280
They have even more stringent criteria.

504
00:19:20.280 --> 00:19:22.680
Whereas before, we set 101 fever,

505
00:19:22.680 --> 00:19:25.234
IDSA says 102 to be able to think about

506
00:19:25.234 --> 00:19:27.420
if it's a bacterial process.

507
00:19:27.420 --> 00:19:30.540
They also don't like the seven days, they like 10 days.

508
00:19:30.540 --> 00:19:31.860
They do like the double sickening.

509
00:19:31.860 --> 00:19:33.960
They also call out immunocompromised patients

510
00:19:33.960 --> 00:19:35.280
as maybe needing antibiotics.

511
00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:38.160
So this is good criteria here.

512
00:19:38.160 --> 00:19:39.840
What antibiotic do we use?

513
00:19:39.840 --> 00:19:43.650
IDSA says Augmentin, amoxicillin-clavulanate.

514
00:19:43.650 --> 00:19:45.660
And the duration is a little bit different.

515
00:19:45.660 --> 00:19:47.040
It's actually shorter for adults,

516
00:19:47.040 --> 00:19:49.200
a slightly bit longer for kids.

517
00:19:49.200 --> 00:19:51.870
High dose, if you have any of these risk factors.

518
00:19:51.870 --> 00:19:53.340
And do the same adjunct therapy

519
00:19:53.340 --> 00:19:54.780
as the viral that we talked about.

520
00:19:54.780 --> 00:19:56.370
Again, help them through the discomfort

521
00:19:56.370 --> 00:19:58.560
of the disease process.

522
00:19:58.560 --> 00:20:00.450
What is second line?

523
00:20:00.450 --> 00:20:03.390
For adults, it's fluoroquinolones and doxycycline.

524
00:20:03.390 --> 00:20:05.190
It is no longer macrolide.

525
00:20:05.190 --> 00:20:08.610
So all these sort of over-prescribing of a Z-PAK

526
00:20:08.610 --> 00:20:10.470
for sinusitis has really burned out

527
00:20:10.470 --> 00:20:11.640
that ability to be helpful.

528
00:20:11.640 --> 00:20:14.490
So Zithromax is not gonna be helpful for you.

529
00:20:14.490 --> 00:20:15.390
For kids, again,

530
00:20:15.390 --> 00:20:17.880
because we wanna avoid fluoroquinolones and doxy,

531
00:20:17.880 --> 00:20:19.380
we're gonna do cephalosporins there,

532
00:20:19.380 --> 00:20:21.830
even though some of that resistance is not great.

533
00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:24.690
What does AAP say?

534
00:20:24.690 --> 00:20:27.840
They actually still say amoxicillin is the first line.

535
00:20:27.840 --> 00:20:30.900
So IDSA says Augmentin for all,

536
00:20:30.900 --> 00:20:34.200
American Academy of Pediatrics says amoxicillin.

537
00:20:34.200 --> 00:20:36.030
So what does AFP say?

538
00:20:36.030 --> 00:20:38.190
Either one is first line in adults and kids.

539
00:20:38.190 --> 00:20:40.050
So they're not gonna test you on that on the boards

540
00:20:40.050 --> 00:20:42.150
of like this one versus this one.

541
00:20:42.150 --> 00:20:43.860
They might test you with the dose,

542
00:20:43.860 --> 00:20:46.110
and you gotta think through that,

543
00:20:46.110 --> 00:20:48.420
but either one is acceptable.

544
00:20:48.420 --> 00:20:50.353
How is that different from chronic rhinosinusitis?

545
00:20:50.353 --> 00:20:52.590
This is 12 weeks or more of symptoms.

546
00:20:52.590 --> 00:20:55.740
And this is not a bacterial process.

547
00:20:55.740 --> 00:20:58.020
This is just a chronic chronic symptom management.

548
00:20:58.020 --> 00:21:00.240
It's an inflammatory disease.

549
00:21:00.240 --> 00:21:02.910
Nasal saline is very helpful for this.

550
00:21:02.910 --> 00:21:04.830
Low pressure, high volume neti pots

551
00:21:04.830 --> 00:21:06.330
actually have the best data

552
00:21:06.330 --> 00:21:08.610
compared to other nasal installations.

553
00:21:08.610 --> 00:21:10.800
That's a strength of recommendation B.

554
00:21:10.800 --> 00:21:12.870
Intranasal steroids are helpful.

555
00:21:12.870 --> 00:21:14.340
Oral steroids have been helpful

556
00:21:14.340 --> 00:21:16.500
only if they have nasal polyps as well,

557
00:21:16.500 --> 00:21:18.900
and that's a short term benefit only.

558
00:21:18.900 --> 00:21:20.280
If you've tried all these things

559
00:21:20.280 --> 00:21:21.330
and you're still struggling,

560
00:21:21.330 --> 00:21:23.400
that's where you might consider ENT.

561
00:21:23.400 --> 00:21:25.530
They could consider endoscopic cultures

562
00:21:25.530 --> 00:21:27.390
to see if it's an unusual bacteria

563
00:21:27.390 --> 00:21:30.063
or a fungal process that would require treatment.

564
00:21:32.010 --> 00:21:34.410
Another rapid fire, allergic rhinitis.

565
00:21:34.410 --> 00:21:38.460
IgE mediated, intermittent, less than four days a week.

566
00:21:38.460 --> 00:21:41.070
Just use nasal saline there. That's pretty clear.

567
00:21:41.070 --> 00:21:43.050
Persistent greater than four days per week

568
00:21:43.050 --> 00:21:44.193
for at least a month.

569
00:21:45.060 --> 00:21:47.130
Allergen avoidance is helpful.

570
00:21:47.130 --> 00:21:49.836
Intranasal steroids are strength of recommendation A here.

571
00:21:49.836 --> 00:21:53.640
Your next line would be an intranasal antihistamine,

572
00:21:53.640 --> 00:21:55.380
more effective and quicker onset,

573
00:21:55.380 --> 00:21:58.110
less side effects than an oral antihistamine.

574
00:21:58.110 --> 00:21:59.610
And then your next line

575
00:21:59.610 --> 00:22:01.380
would be your second-generation antihistamine.

576
00:22:01.380 --> 00:22:04.020
So that strengths of recommendation B.

577
00:22:04.020 --> 00:22:05.780
All this stuff that we heard about for a while,

578
00:22:05.780 --> 00:22:08.370
like mattress covers, pillow covers,

579
00:22:08.370 --> 00:22:11.250
HEPA filters actually didn't seem to make any difference.

580
00:22:11.250 --> 00:22:13.650
That's the Choosing Wisely campaign from ENT.

581
00:22:13.650 --> 00:22:15.700
So we're not the only ones who have that.

582
00:22:16.770 --> 00:22:18.660
Now, the rapid fire, chronic cough.

583
00:22:18.660 --> 00:22:21.270
Cough greater than eight weeks duration.

584
00:22:21.270 --> 00:22:24.900
You do an examination, you do a chest X-ray on all,

585
00:22:24.900 --> 00:22:26.460
you make sure they're not on an eighth.

586
00:22:26.460 --> 00:22:27.900
Even if they've been on it for years,

587
00:22:27.900 --> 00:22:30.510
it could still be the cause of their chronic cough.

588
00:22:30.510 --> 00:22:31.890
What are the most common causes?

589
00:22:31.890 --> 00:22:34.050
What we used to call postnasal drip now

590
00:22:34.050 --> 00:22:37.890
has this new fun name, upper airway cough syndrome.

591
00:22:37.890 --> 00:22:39.960
Nasal steroids is your treatment.

592
00:22:39.960 --> 00:22:41.160
Asthma, you are gonna get that

593
00:22:41.160 --> 00:22:42.360
out of your history, hopefully.

594
00:22:42.360 --> 00:22:45.090
If you have any concern, get that spirometry.

595
00:22:45.090 --> 00:22:47.520
Non-asthmatic eosinophilic bronchitis

596
00:22:47.520 --> 00:22:49.070
we're kinda learning more about

597
00:22:50.126 --> 00:22:51.518
is a source of chronic cough and GERD.

598
00:22:51.518 --> 00:22:53.130
I think we've realized that one for a while.

599
00:22:53.130 --> 00:22:54.210
And here's some options.

600
00:22:54.210 --> 00:22:56.820
If they don't improve, you might escalate your workup.

601
00:22:56.820 --> 00:22:59.010
And if all that exam is normal

602
00:22:59.010 --> 00:23:01.590
and they're just a cough, cough, cough kind of person,

603
00:23:01.590 --> 00:23:04.934
gabapentin has some expert opinion stuff on it.

604
00:23:04.934 --> 00:23:07.860
Pregabalin, for Lyrica also.

605
00:23:07.860 --> 00:23:10.713
And then speech therapy, expert opinion only.

606
00:23:12.120 --> 00:23:13.860
Laryngitis.

607
00:23:13.860 --> 00:23:16.920
Acute hoarseness for less than three to four weeks.

608
00:23:16.920 --> 00:23:18.450
What they sometimes test you on here

609
00:23:18.450 --> 00:23:19.530
is what is the treatment?

610
00:23:19.530 --> 00:23:23.700
The answer is complete voice rest, not whispering.

611
00:23:23.700 --> 00:23:26.340
Whispering, hurt your vocal cords more.

612
00:23:26.340 --> 00:23:28.530
So that's all you gotta do. No other treatments are helpful.

613
00:23:28.530 --> 00:23:30.570
Just tell them you may not speak for a few days,

614
00:23:30.570 --> 00:23:32.220
and that usually gets better.

615
00:23:32.220 --> 00:23:34.087
I wish someone would tell me that, huh?

616
00:23:34.087 --> 00:23:37.170
Chronic, greater than three to four weeks,

617
00:23:37.170 --> 00:23:39.030
you have to worry about other things here, right?

618
00:23:39.030 --> 00:23:41.790
And the key point here is if you have a high risk person

619
00:23:41.790 --> 00:23:44.089
that's a smoker, someone with alcohol use disorder,

620
00:23:44.089 --> 00:23:47.250
or any homeostasis, you don't wait that three months

621
00:23:47.250 --> 00:23:48.660
to think about a laryngoscope.

622
00:23:48.660 --> 00:23:50.580
You might consider that at the two-week mark

623
00:23:50.580 --> 00:23:51.870
because they have a much higher risk

624
00:23:51.870 --> 00:23:54.150
of having disease process.

625
00:23:54.150 --> 00:23:56.100
Voice therapy for those chronic patients

626
00:23:56.100 --> 00:23:58.170
actually a strength of recommendation A here,

627
00:23:58.170 --> 00:23:59.610
has really good benefit for them.

628
00:23:59.610 --> 00:24:00.693
So think about that.

629
00:24:02.460 --> 00:24:04.320
Ooh, we get to hear about this again apparently, no,

630
00:24:04.320 --> 00:24:06.200
I'm not gonna whisper for you again.

631
00:24:06.200 --> 00:24:07.860
ENT emergencies.

632
00:24:07.860 --> 00:24:09.330
Foreign bodies in the ear

633
00:24:09.330 --> 00:24:10.920
is a pretty common thing with kids.

634
00:24:10.920 --> 00:24:14.010
What we're seeing a lot of is these little button batteries,

635
00:24:14.010 --> 00:24:15.990
those are pretty harmful.

636
00:24:15.990 --> 00:24:18.789
They can cause very rapid pressure necrosis

637
00:24:18.789 --> 00:24:21.330
due to the electrical currents in them.

638
00:24:21.330 --> 00:24:22.530
So if you have a kiddo

639
00:24:22.530 --> 00:24:24.480
that you think has a button battery in their ear,

640
00:24:24.480 --> 00:24:26.250
that's like an ENT emergency.

641
00:24:26.250 --> 00:24:27.330
If you can't get that out,

642
00:24:27.330 --> 00:24:31.020
they need to see ENT like within the next couple of hours.

643
00:24:31.020 --> 00:24:32.340
Commonly with our wrestlers,

644
00:24:32.340 --> 00:24:34.470
you'll see this auricular hematoma.

645
00:24:34.470 --> 00:24:36.240
Make sure you do I&amp;D those,

646
00:24:36.240 --> 00:24:38.880
otherwise you'll end up with that cauliflower ear.

647
00:24:38.880 --> 00:24:41.430
Those scrum caps are kind of preventative for that.

648
00:24:42.900 --> 00:24:45.870
Common, really common, obviously, see is this epistaxis.

649
00:24:45.870 --> 00:24:48.810
Important things you'll see here, if it's an anterior bleed,

650
00:24:48.810 --> 00:24:50.160
you've got a lot of treatment options.

651
00:24:50.160 --> 00:24:52.756
You've got packing, silver nitrate, TXA,

652
00:24:52.756 --> 00:24:54.900
electrocautery 'cause you can get to it.

653
00:24:54.900 --> 00:24:56.070
If it's a posterior bleed,

654
00:24:56.070 --> 00:24:57.480
you're gonna need to do a balloon packing

655
00:24:57.480 --> 00:25:00.000
or like tampon in the nose, that kind of thing.

656
00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:02.340
Somehow, these button batteries end up the nose as well

657
00:25:02.340 --> 00:25:03.173
in our children.

658
00:25:03.173 --> 00:25:06.240
So again, very important to get that out quickly.

659
00:25:06.240 --> 00:25:08.580
If you do see a nasal fracture, it's kind of interesting,

660
00:25:08.580 --> 00:25:09.510
you don't need an x-ray.

661
00:25:09.510 --> 00:25:11.250
That can be diagnosed clinically.

662
00:25:11.250 --> 00:25:12.930
But if there is a septal hematoma,

663
00:25:12.930 --> 00:25:14.400
you do wanna drain that as well,

664
00:25:14.400 --> 00:25:17.300
or you're gonna have a permanent sort of saddle deformity.

665
00:25:18.240 --> 00:25:19.230
Dental trauma.

666
00:25:19.230 --> 00:25:21.060
There's two things I want you to know from this slide.

667
00:25:21.060 --> 00:25:24.540
Number one, if there's blood on the surface of the tooth,

668
00:25:24.540 --> 00:25:26.220
we have a core or pulp injury,

669
00:25:26.220 --> 00:25:28.590
then they need to see a dentist ASAP.

670
00:25:28.590 --> 00:25:31.830
If the tooth has already come out and it's not a baby tooth,

671
00:25:31.830 --> 00:25:32.850
put it back in.

672
00:25:32.850 --> 00:25:33.810
That's another important one.

673
00:25:33.810 --> 00:25:34.950
Don't scrub it,

674
00:25:34.950 --> 00:25:36.210
leave whatever goo is on it,

675
00:25:36.210 --> 00:25:37.980
just gently clean it and put it back in

676
00:25:37.980 --> 00:25:39.453
and then go see the dentist.

677
00:25:41.220 --> 00:25:43.018
Next question here.

678
00:25:43.018 --> 00:25:44.910
It's your last patient of the day.

679
00:25:44.910 --> 00:25:46.920
Your nurse says they're added on for dizziness,

680
00:25:46.920 --> 00:25:48.870
and you're like, "Oh, Lord."

681
00:25:48.870 --> 00:25:51.480
But luckily, 57-year-old female patient of yours

682
00:25:51.480 --> 00:25:54.210
presents with dizziness and a sensation she is spinning.

683
00:25:54.210 --> 00:25:55.830
It occurs when she turns in bed

684
00:25:55.830 --> 00:25:58.350
or lifts her head to look at an upper cabinet.

685
00:25:58.350 --> 00:26:00.570
Episodes are brief but are becoming more frequent.

686
00:26:00.570 --> 00:26:02.160
No tinnitus or hearing loss.

687
00:26:02.160 --> 00:26:04.263
What is your most likely diagnosis?

688
00:26:09.060 --> 00:26:12.720
Yes, the dizziness gods were in our favor today, BPPV.

689
00:26:12.720 --> 00:26:13.950
Good stuff.

690
00:26:13.950 --> 00:26:15.210
So just very quickly,

691
00:26:15.210 --> 00:26:17.670
between a peripheral and a central vertigo.

692
00:26:17.670 --> 00:26:20.520
Peripheral vertigo is actually less severe

693
00:26:20.520 --> 00:26:22.230
and a lot of ear symptoms, right?

694
00:26:22.230 --> 00:26:24.210
Fullness, hearing loss, you name it.

695
00:26:24.210 --> 00:26:25.080
Central vertigo,

696
00:26:25.080 --> 00:26:27.750
these people are usually not walking into your office,

697
00:26:27.750 --> 00:26:29.555
they're in a wheelchair and they're barfing as they come in

698
00:26:29.555 --> 00:26:31.680
'cause it's so intense.

699
00:26:31.680 --> 00:26:34.533
So that can help you to know who needs a big workup.

700
00:26:36.090 --> 00:26:38.640
This is kind of fun. They like to test us on this a lot.

701
00:26:38.640 --> 00:26:40.950
I don't know why this has showed up more than once.

702
00:26:40.950 --> 00:26:43.350
But for BPPV, if you look at their eye,

703
00:26:43.350 --> 00:26:47.310
they typically have a torsional up-beating nystagmus,

704
00:26:47.310 --> 00:26:50.894
and that's because BPPV is stones in the canalith, right?

705
00:26:50.894 --> 00:26:51.870
This canalith eyes,

706
00:26:51.870 --> 00:26:55.020
And it's usually in that posterior semi-circular canal.

707
00:26:55.020 --> 00:26:57.903
And that's what causes that nystagmus in that direction.

708
00:26:59.040 --> 00:27:00.270
Vestibular neuritis,

709
00:27:00.270 --> 00:27:03.090
another common cause of peripheral vertigo.

710
00:27:03.090 --> 00:27:05.010
It usually is short-lived, one to two days.

711
00:27:05.010 --> 00:27:07.290
So that's one we don't have to worry too much about

712
00:27:07.290 --> 00:27:09.153
in terms of its long-term issues.

713
00:27:10.110 --> 00:27:12.570
Meniere's, much more of a chronic disease,

714
00:27:12.570 --> 00:27:13.980
pretty hard to treat.

715
00:27:13.980 --> 00:27:16.350
Big thing about that is that ear fullness.

716
00:27:16.350 --> 00:27:18.600
So they'll really be bothered by that ear fullness.

717
00:27:18.600 --> 00:27:19.680
If so, think about that.

718
00:27:19.680 --> 00:27:21.870
And that's an endolymphatic hydrops.

719
00:27:21.870 --> 00:27:24.870
So too much fluid, right, in that area.

720
00:27:24.870 --> 00:27:27.390
Acoustic neuroma we've hinted to already.

721
00:27:27.390 --> 00:27:30.870
We know that tinnitus and hearing loss are major complaints,

722
00:27:30.870 --> 00:27:34.350
vertigo is a minor complaint, so that can help you a bit.

723
00:27:34.350 --> 00:27:37.920
The old Ramsey Hunt Syndrome, herpes zoster oticus.

724
00:27:37.920 --> 00:27:39.030
I don't think I've ever seen it,

725
00:27:39.030 --> 00:27:40.920
but we get tested on it a lot.

726
00:27:40.920 --> 00:27:43.530
So someone has vertigo and they can't taste

727
00:27:43.530 --> 00:27:47.100
and they have facial paralysis, that's your slam dunk there.

728
00:27:47.100 --> 00:27:50.024
Central vertigo, you have to worry about infarctions.

729
00:27:50.024 --> 00:27:53.403
Sometimes vestibular migraines can do this to you.

730
00:27:54.330 --> 00:27:56.970
This is important in that if you're working up vertigo,

731
00:27:56.970 --> 00:27:59.850
it is really just history and physical exam.

732
00:27:59.850 --> 00:28:02.310
Labs are helpful less than 1% of the time.

733
00:28:02.310 --> 00:28:03.600
You only need to image them

734
00:28:03.600 --> 00:28:05.430
if there are other neuro signs and symptoms,

735
00:28:05.430 --> 00:28:08.580
or if profound hearing loss is a part of that.

736
00:28:08.580 --> 00:28:10.380
The Dix-Hallpike is wonderful.

737
00:28:10.380 --> 00:28:12.960
It has great negative predictive value.

738
00:28:12.960 --> 00:28:14.430
So if you think their BPPV

739
00:28:14.430 --> 00:28:16.500
and you do a Dix-Hallpike and it's negative,

740
00:28:16.500 --> 00:28:18.153
think about another diagnosis.

741
00:28:19.560 --> 00:28:21.000
Medications for vertigo are crap

742
00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:23.340
'cause they have so many side effects, right?

743
00:28:23.340 --> 00:28:24.840
So it's really only gonna be considered

744
00:28:24.840 --> 00:28:26.820
for types of vertigo that are very chronic.

745
00:28:26.820 --> 00:28:29.103
You're not gonna do this for BPPV, obviously.

746
00:28:30.570 --> 00:28:32.190
What are you gonna do for BPPV?

747
00:28:32.190 --> 00:28:33.300
The Epley maneuvers.

748
00:28:33.300 --> 00:28:34.740
You will walk out of that office

749
00:28:34.740 --> 00:28:36.090
feeling like a hero that day

750
00:28:36.090 --> 00:28:37.470
'cause they walk in feeling terrible.

751
00:28:37.470 --> 00:28:39.990
You put 'em through the Epley, they hit you at the time,

752
00:28:39.990 --> 00:28:42.780
but then they feel better, and they love you when they go.

753
00:28:42.780 --> 00:28:44.070
PT is also great.

754
00:28:44.070 --> 00:28:46.200
Vestibular rehab has really great data

755
00:28:46.200 --> 00:28:48.270
for peripheral sources of vertigo,

756
00:28:48.270 --> 00:28:50.640
medium data for central sources of vertigo,

757
00:28:50.640 --> 00:28:51.753
but it's good stuff.

758
00:28:52.650 --> 00:28:55.290
Bell's palsy, we're coming in the home stretch here.

759
00:28:55.290 --> 00:28:57.180
Idiopathic facial paralysis,

760
00:28:57.180 --> 00:28:58.740
what do you need to know about it?

761
00:28:58.740 --> 00:29:01.320
Antivirals and corticosteroids are more effective

762
00:29:01.320 --> 00:29:02.700
than either one alone.

763
00:29:02.700 --> 00:29:05.220
Number needed to treat there as 15.

764
00:29:05.220 --> 00:29:07.560
Antivirals alone are not helpful.

765
00:29:07.560 --> 00:29:09.330
That strength of recommendation A.

766
00:29:09.330 --> 00:29:10.860
Here's your Board Frequent Flyers

767
00:29:10.860 --> 00:29:12.360
to put in your study folder,

768
00:29:12.360 --> 00:29:14.680
and I thank you so much for your attention today.

769
00:29:14.680 --> 00:29:17.680
(audience clapping)

770
00:29:19.227 --> 00:29:22.310
(gentle music)

771
00:29:22.310 --> 00:29:25.393
